'''Pamela Harrison''' (born 28 Nov 1915, Orpington - died 28 Aug 1990, Firle, East Sussex) was an English pianist, music teacher and composer.

==Biography==
Pamela Harrison was born in [[Orpington, England]]. She studied with [[Gordon Jacob]] and [[Arthur Benjamin]] at the [[Royal School of Music]], London. During [[World War II]], she worked as a school teacher.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IvoQQU1QL_QC&pg=PA210&dq=pamela+harrison+composer&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zIfxUK3-Dovc8ASIqoHYAQ&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=pamela%20harrison%20composer&f=false|title=The Norton/Grove dictionary of women composers|format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|first=Julie Anne|last=Sadie|first2=Rhian|last2=Samuel|year=1994|pate=210|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref>

Harrison's work was influenced by French music and composers [[E.J. Moeran]], [[Arnold Bax]] and [[John Ireland]]. She made her debut as a composer with ''String Quartet'' in 1944. She composed a variety of music, including Chamber, Orchestral and Vocal Music, and her setting include [[Baudelaire]], [[Herrick]], [[Dowson]] and [[Edward Thomas]]. Her work for small orchestra ''A Suite for Timothy'' was composed for the first birthday of her son.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pamela Harrison|url=http://www.naxos.com/person/Pamela_Harrison/18736.htm|publisher=Naxos|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref>

In 1990 Harrison died in a car accident in [[Firle]], [[East Sussex]]. 

==Works==
Selected works include:

*''String Quartet'' (1944)
*''Six Poems of Baudelaire'' (1944-45)
*''A Suite for Timothy'' (1948)

==Recordings==
Selected recordings include: 

*''English String Miiatures, Vol. 5'', Naxos

